org.safs.tools.drivers

Class JSAFSDriver

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.safs.tools.drivers.AbstractDriver
      • org.safs.tools.drivers.DefaultDriver
        • org.safs.tools.drivers.JSAFSDriver
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DriverInterface, PathInterface

    public class JSAFSDriver
extends DefaultDriver
    A class that provides easy access to SAFS functionality for non-SAFS programs and frameworks.

    JSAFSDriver jsafs = new JSAFSDriver("JSAFS");
    jsafs.run();
    //do whatever you want with and without SAFS...
    jsafs.processCommand(AbstractCommand, String);
    jsafs.shutdown();

    Using JSAFS.

      • systemExitOnShutdown

        public boolean systemExitOnShutdown
        When SAFS Monitor usage is enabled (useSAFSMonitor=true), and the JSAFSDriver has detected the test or a user has initiated a JSAFSDriver shutdown through this mechanism, the default implementation of the JSAFSDriver processCommand(AbstractCommand, String) is to initiate System finalization followed by a System exit--a complete shutdown of the JVM running the tests.

        If the developer does NOT want a such a complete shutdown to occur upon a JSAFSDriver shutdown, then this field should be set to 'false'.
        The default setting is 'true'.

        See Also:
        DefaultDriver.useSAFSMonitor, processCommand(AbstractCommand, String)

      • closeMap

        public void closeMap(java.lang.String mapname)
              throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Convenience routine to close an App Map. This can be used instead of using the Driver Command "CloseApplicationMap". Note: Closing an app map removes it from any App Map chain. If the closed App Map was the "default" app map then the last App Map still existing in the App Map chain becomes the "default" App Map.
        Parameters:
        mapname - -- Name of app map to close and remove from any app map chain. The name used must be the same name used in the openMap call or the SetApplicationMap Driver Command. The mapname, however, is not case-sensitive.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if mapname is null or cannot be resolved to a valid App Map filepath by the driver.
        See Also:
        #openAppMap(String), SAFSMAPS.closeMap(org.safs.tools.UniqueIDInterface)

        protected java.lang.String processExpression(java.lang.String testRecord,
                                 java.lang.String separator)
        This method is used to resolve the expressions within a test record, something like ^var=Text or ^varPrefix & ^varSuffix will be processed by the VariableService, some works like assignment of variable will be done during that period. One thing to take care: after the resolveExpression, each field will be quoted by ", for example, "C, AppMapResolve, OFF" --> ""C", "AppMapResolve", "OFF"" we should call method getTrimmedUnquotedInputRecordToken() of TestRecordHelper to get each field.
        Parameters:

        separator - the separator used in the test record
        Returns:
        the resolved test record string

      • resolveExpression

        public java.lang.String resolveExpression(java.lang.String expression)
        Resolve an expression. "DDVariable" will be always evaluated.
        Note: Only when AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is true, the expression will be resolved as "math string".
        No mater what AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is, the expression will be resolved as "DDVariable"
        For example, String result = resolveExpression("^var=3+5");
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is false, the result is "3+5", and variable "var" contains string "3+5"
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is true, the result is "8", and variable "var" contains string "8"
        Note: Be careful, the expression will be TRIMMED and then evaluated.
        For example, String result = resolveExpression(" 3+5 ");
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is false, the result is string "3+5".
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is true, the result is string "8".
        Parameters:
        expression - String, the expression to be resolved.
        Returns:
        String, the resolved expressions.

      • resolveExpression

        protected java.lang.String resolveExpression(java.lang.String expressions,
                                 java.lang.String separator)
        Resolve a set of expressions delimited by separator. "DDVariable" will be always evaluated.
        Note: Only when AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is true, each expression will be resolved as "math string".
        No mater what AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is, each expression will be resolved as "DDVariable"
        For example, String result = resolveExpression("^var=3+5", ",");
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is false, the result is ""3+5"" (double-quoted string), and variable "var" contains string "3+5" (normal string)
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is true, the result is ""8"" (double-quoted string), and variable "var" contains string "8" (normal string)
        Note: Be careful, each expression will be TRIMMED and then evaluated, the evaluated value will be WRAPPED in DOUBLE-QUOTE to return.
        For example, String result = resolveExpression(" 3+5 , > ,9-3 ", ",");
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is false, the result is string ""3+5",">","9-3"", each field has been wrapped in double quote.
        If AbstractDriver.isExpressionsEnabled() is true, the result is string ""8",">","6"", each field has been wrapped in double quote.
        Parameters:
        expressions - String, a set of expression delimited by separator, such as "expression1, expression2, expression3"
        separator - String, the separator used to delimit expressions
        Returns:
        String, the resolved expressions. Each field will be double quoted!

      • checkSAFSMonitorStatus

        public java.lang.String checkSAFSMonitorStatus()
                                        throws SAFSException
        Programmatically conform to user-initiated PAUSE, RUN, STEP, STEP RETRY input from SAFS Monitor.

        This method is used to check for and comply with user input to SAFS Monitor, but cannot provide PAUSE_ON_FAILURE support.

        The PAUSE and other features are only checked if DefaultDriver.useSAFSMonitor is 'true'.

        A given status will perform the following functions:

          STOP (SHUTDOWN_HOOK) - Throw the SAFSException.
          PAUSE - sleep 1 second and loop to check again (indefinitely).
          RUNNING - Do nothing. Immediately return with RUNNING status.
          STEP - While PAUSED, immediately return with STEPPING status.
          STEPPING - Enter PAUSE mode when this method is called again.
          STEP_RETRY - While PAUSED, immediately return with STEPPING_RETRY status.
          STEPPING_RETRY - Enter PAUSE mode when this method is called again.
        Returns:
        the current status of the SAFS_DRIVER_CONTROL variable.
        Throws:
        SAFSException - if SHUTDOWN_HOOK was detected. This routine only throws the Exception. It does not attempt a JVM shutdown.

      • processCommand

        public TestRecordHelper processCommand(AbstractCommand command,
                              java.lang.String separator)
        This method can process DriverCommand or ComponentFunction just as runDriverCommand() or runComponentFunction(), further more it includes the functionality of SAFSMonitor so users can interctively PAUSE, STEP, DEBUG their script and SHUTDOWN the engine hook.

        This method will automatically be called from runDriverCommand or runComponentFunction if DefaultDriver.useSAFSMonitor=true -- which it is by default. If the developer wants to disable this feature the developer should set useSAFSMonitor to 'false'.

        If this method detects a user initiated shutdown request via SAFS Monitor, or if the running test initiates the same type of shutdown request, this method will initiate a full JVM finalization and System.exit if systemExitOnShutdown=true -- which it is by default. If the developer wants to disable the automatic JVM finalization and shutdown feature then the developer should set systemExitOnShutdown to 'false'.

        Parameters:
        command - An instance of AbstractCommand which is abstract, so it is
        an instance of its child class, DriverCommand or ComponentFunction
        separator - The separator used to create test-record from AbstractCommand.
        Returns:
        TestRecordHelper with result information. TestRecordData.getStatusCode() and TestRecordData.getStatusInfo()
        See Also:
        DefaultDriver.useSAFSMonitor, systemExitOnShutdown, runDriverCommand(DriverCommand), runComponentFunction(ComponentFunction)

  • routeToPreferredEngines

    protected long routeToPreferredEngines(TestRecordHelper trd)
    Route the input record to preferred engines only in the order of preference.
    Normally, we forward the input record to each engine until one of the engines signals that it processed the record.

  • routeToEngines

    protected long routeToEngines(TestRecordHelper trd,
                  boolean sendAll)
    Route the input record to one or more engines, or all engines.
    Normally, we forward the input record to each engine until one of the engines signals that it processed the record.

    If 'sendAll' is TRUE, it means the record needs to be processed by EVERY engine, regardless of the response from any one engine. For example, if the driver must tell each engine to clear a cache, or something.

    if 'sendAll' is FALSE, we will not route to any engine that is 'preferred' because all 'preferred' engines should have already been tried.

    See Also:
    routeToPreferredEngines(TestRecordHelper)

  • run

    public void run()
    Called to initialize the JSAFSDriver and make it ready for use.
    This overridden implementation does not invoke processTest(). Thus, the driver is ready to use for ad-hoc calls to SAFS. The driver must be shutdown() when testing is completed.

    Invokes:
    DefaultDriver.validateRootConfigureParameters()
    DefaultDriver.validateLogParameters()
    DefaultDriver.initializeRuntimeInterface()
    DefaultDriver.launchSAFSMonitor()
    DefaultDriver.initializePresetVariables()
    DefaultDriver.initializeMiscConfigInfo()
    DefaultDriver.initializeRuntimeEngines()
    DefaultDriver.openTestLogs()
    initialize statuscounter

    Overrides:
    run in class DefaultDriver
    See Also:
    SAFSDRIVER.main(String[])
